# Loom — the sink tree

Loom composes code along the frame and writes it out through sinks. A sink names the file it produces; where that file lands is the author's to compose, in the document, not a configuration kept beside it. A section may name a directory rather than a file, and so become a vertex that places a whole chapter of files beneath it. The book that orders the corpus for a reader is the same structure that routes it to disk.

_The present tense states the design. The grammar and a first per-module routing are built; the chapter model below revises that routing — a higher-order sink places a chapter, not a whole module — and is the target the next revision moves toward._

## Sinks have orders

A sink binds composed code to an output location. Loom has one kind today and gains a second.

A **tangle sink** is a section whose specifier is a file path, `{src/Main.ts}`. It composes its members and emits one file. It is a leaf of the tree: it consumes the composition graph, and nothing consumes it. This is the sink Loom already has.

A **higher-order sink** is a section whose specifier is a directory, `{packages/loom-cli/}`, told apart from a file path by its trailing slash. It emits no file of its own and inlines no code. It is an interior vertex: it points at a chapter and places that chapter's tangle sinks under its directory, in its language. A tangle sink names one file; a higher-order sink names where a whole chapter of files lands.

## Chapters and the tangling tree

A higher-order sink points at a chapter. An anchor in the sink — `::[Parsing the line]` — names a section by its title, and that section must be a top-level heading, an H1. The H1 opens a chapter: itself and every section after it, in document order, until the next pointed H1 short-circuits the range and opens the next chapter. The pointed H1s partition a module into chapters; a heading between them, at any level, is absorbed into the chapter it falls in. An author nests headings however reads best — only the H1s a book points at are structural.

A higher-order sink places its chapter's tangle sinks under its directory, in its language. Where a chapter declares `{src/main.ts}`, the sink `{packages/loom-cli/}` over it writes `packages/loom-cli/src/main.ts`. The sink inlines nothing and emits nothing; it prefixes and places, one hop down. Prefixes accumulate when one higher-order sink points at another, so a directory nested in a directory nests its files in turn.

The first chapter a book points into a module should open at the module's first section, an H1, so no section is stranded ahead of it, outside every chapter. A higher-order sink may not, through its members, reach itself; a cycle is refused before any file is written, the same way an unresolved anchor is.

A member names a chapter; it carries no specifier of its own. The sink's directory and language place the whole chapter at once, so there is nothing to override per member — the per-section reroute an earlier draft allowed only added noise. An anchor is never a file, and its name is never a filename; it is the edge and the symbol, nothing more.

## The book is a pattern, not a name

There is no reserved `book.loom`. A book is any loom that carries higher-order sinks — a router built from directory vertices. A project may keep one, several, or none. With none, a tangle sink falls back to the workspace default, the behaviour Loom has today. The book adds an organisation above the sinks; it never replaces the sink.

## The specifier says output; the title says identity

A heading's specifier carries the output, and its shape names the role:

- a bare word is a **language** — `{Scala}`;
- a path with an extension is a **tangle sink** — `{src/Main.ts}`;
- a path with a trailing slash is a **higher-order sink** — `{packages/loom-cli/}`;
- two parts are a **language and a location** — `{rust, loom/cli/}`.

A higher-order sink wears the two-part specifier — its directory and its default language, `{rust, loom/cli/}`. Its members do not: a member is a plain `::[Chapter]` anchor naming a chapter's H1, and the sink's directory and language place the whole chapter, so a member has nothing to override. An anchor that carries a specifier outside this — on a tangle sink, a plain section, anywhere a specifier cannot route — is a fault, not a thing Loom ignores.

The specifier is output, and output is never a symbol. A section's identity — what an anchor resolves to, what go-to-definition reaches, what rename renames — is its title, folded through `normaliseTitle`, the one function that already names every tagless section. So go-to-definition on a member lands on its chapter's heading by title; the `{packages/loom-cli/}` prefix navigates no more than `{src/Main.ts}` does, because both are paths.

## A higher-order sink is the package root

The tree is not a new mechanism beside tangling. It is where the old `packageRoot` comes from. A file resolves to a `BuildSettings` — its delimiters, its primary language, and the `packageRoot` its sinks tangle under — and `outputPath(packageRoot, entry, sink)` places each file. A chapter's higher-order sink is that `packageRoot`, and its language is that primary language, composed in the document instead of resolved from configuration. A tangle sink in no chapter keeps the default `packageRoot` — the directory holding its `corpus/` — so a bookless corpus tangles as it does today, and a book overrides the default only for the chapters it places.

## Three orders, never conflated

A corpus is read in three orders, and the sink tree is one of them. The **narrative order** is how the book reads, top to bottom. The **dependency order** is the import graph, what a module needs to compose. The **tangle order** is the sink tree, where each file lands. A chapter may read in part one, import from three looms, and tangle into a fourth package, and none of the three orders constrains the others. The sink tree joins the frame as a de dicto structure — the frame says how code composes, the sink tree says where it goes.

## Sinks are symbols

A higher-order sink and its members are Loom symbols, served by Loom's own language service beside the diagnostics and the frame queries it already answers. An anchor resolves to a section by title; a section reports every anchor that composes it. Renaming a section rewrites its heading and every anchor that names it in one edit, the name and its references kept in step. A file renamed in the editor is the other direction: it rides a file-rename hook that mends the `import "./old.loom"` references naming it. A section's title and its file stay separate — the title is a symbol, the path a specifier the author writes — so renaming one never moves the other.

## Health

The sink tree adds its own entries to the one fault catalog, each a leaf diagnostic with a position and a message, in the editor and at the tangle alike.

Some are errors, refused before any file is written. A member that resolves to no section. Two titles that normalise alike. A higher-order sink that reaches itself through its members. Two higher-order sinks that point the same chapter — its files would have two homes. Two sinks that tangle to one path. An anchor that carries a specifier where none can route. A book that points into its own file.

Some are warnings, surfaced but not fatal. A pointed section that is not an H1 — a chapter should open at a top-level heading. A book whose first chapter into a module does not open that module's first section, stranding the sections ahead of it outside every chapter. A higher-order sink with no members. A chapter that places no file, because nothing in its range is a tangle sink.

## Invariants

- One normalisation names titles, anchors, slugs, and symbols — `normaliseTitle`, nowhere a second rule.
- A specifier is output; a title is identity. Paths never navigate; titles always do.
- A chapter is a contiguous run of sections in document order, opened by a pointed H1 and closed by the next; it belongs to one higher-order sink, never two.
- The sink tree is derived from the parse AST — higher-order sinks, the chapters their anchors point at, and the tangle sinks in range — never from a configuration kept alongside.
- A broken sink tree refuses the tangle and degrades the editor; a corpus with no book tangles as it does today.
